The philosophy of the Vi<218><207>upur<193><207>a is practically ç
the same as the Ved<193>nta of the Upani<218>ads.
God the Absolute, though called Vi<218><207>u here, is not just the ç
Vi<218><207>u of the Trinity responsible for the sustenance ofthe ç
created world. He is Parabrahman, of the nature of j<210><193>na (knowledge ç
or consciousness) and absolutely pure. The appearance of this world ç
as an entity separate from him is only an illusion (1.2-6).
Brahm<193>, Vi<218><207>u and Mahe·vara of the Trinity are actually ç
the three aspects of this Param<193>tman as associated with thethree ç
gu<207>as (rajas, sattva and tamas) (vide 1.2.56 and 66; 1.4.15; ç
1.9.56).
The description of the process of creation is similar to that of the ç
S<193><209>khya philosophy (1.2.28-70). However, in this pur<193><207>a ç
Vi<218><207>u is the original and absolute cause. The world evolves ç
out of him† called Vi<218><207>u (1.1.31) or K<216><218><207>a (4.12.4)† ç
through his power called pradh<193>na or prak<216>ti.
Even the infinite numbers of the j<200>vas (individual beings) are ç
the reflections of the one Vi<218><207>u seen due to avidy<193> or ç
nescience.
The pur<193><207>a accepts the karma (or actions) sanctioned by the ç
scriptures and bhakti or devotion to God (Vi<218><207>u) as the primary ç
means of mok<218>a or liberation. Ni<218>k<193>makarma (selfless action) ç
purifies the mind. Vi<218><207>u gets established in such a mind. ç
Dhy<193>na or meditation on the beautiful form of Vi<218><207>u along ç
with the repetition of the dv<193>da·<193>k<218>ar<200>mantra (mantra ç
of twelve syllables viz., o<221> namo bhagavate v<193>sudev<193>ya) ç
will lead to j<210><193>na and mok<218>a.
However, the role of bhakti has beenhighlighted, through the story ç
of Prahl<193>da.
