@SB8.5 = Description of Kaliyuga
Though the Vi<218><207>upur<193><207>a gives a long description ç
of the Kaliyuga, the age wherein people become unrighteous and evil ç
to the core (vide 5.1.10-58), it also points out the three advantages ç
that people have in that age. They are: People get the highest spiritual ç
benefits just by singing the names and glories of God; women get all ç
the merit of the good deeds by serving their husbands sincerely; ·<220>dras ç
attain religious merit by performing their duties well.
@SB8.5 = The Vi<218><207>upur<193><207>a and the Bh<193>gavata
The Bh<193>gavata seems to be an elabo- ration of the stories and ç
ideas contained in the Vi<218><207>upur<193><207>a. Whereas the ç
latter deals only with five avat<193>ras or incarnations out of the ç
well-known ten, the Bh<193>gavata deals in detail with all the ten ç
and a few more. Though bhakti or devotion finds an important place ç
in the Vi<218><207>upur<193><207>a, in the Bh<193>gavata it is ç
allpervading. However, it has to be conceded that the language of ç
the latter is quite archaic and tough whereas that of the former is ç
simple and elegant.
@SB8.5 = Literary Grace
The Vi<218><207>upur<193><207>a has certain special features. Its ç
language, though simple and elegant, is also highly poetic. Descriptions ç
of nature are not only beautiful but alsocontain excellent similes ç
bearing on philosophical and ethical principles (vide 5.10.2-15). ç
There are verses praising Bharatakha<207><195>a (India) as karmabh<220>mi ç
(the land of good deeds) and that one is born here only out of religious ç
merit (2.3.23, 24).
